  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "In `get_eligible_validator_indices` the previous epoch is used, then \"converted\" (not strictly the same for genesis epoch) back to current epoch:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nprevious_epoch + 1 < v.withdrawable_epoch\r\n```\r\nNow the rewards and penalties, the only place where `get_eligible_validator_indices` is used, we don't run anything for genesis epoch:\r\n```\r\ndef process_rewards_and_penalties(state: BeaconState) -> None:\r\n    if get_current_epoch(state) == GENESIS_EPOCH:\r\n        return\r\n```\r\nDoes this mean the `previous_epoch + 1` could just have been a `current_epoch`, as there shouldn't be any effective difference?\r\n\r\nContext: @terencechain is comparing Prysm and spec/zrnt balances code, upgrading to v0.12, and after discussing the inclusion delay part (which seems to be a subset of eligible validators regardless of the eligibility check, although a tricky/awkward edge case), this difference showed up.\r\n\r\nIf there is any special reason to use `previous_epoch + 1` instead of `current_epoch` I'd like to know, and we should add a comment as part of the spec function descriptions PR.\r\n",
